1
00:00:16,267 --> 00:00:17,602
<i>Look at them.</i>

2
00:00:17,685 --> 00:00:19,854
<i>Praying for a miracle
that isn't coming.</i>

3
00:00:20,813 --> 00:00:21,856
Who knows?

4
00:00:21,940 --> 00:00:25,193
Maybe it's my curse to leave
one betrayal behind,

5
00:00:25,527 --> 00:00:28,821
only to find a greater one
here amongst the stars.

6
00:00:29,614 --> 00:00:31,324
They could've stopped this.

7
00:00:32,116 --> 00:00:35,078
But none of them had the strength
to do what must be done.

8
00:00:36,538 --> 00:00:37,539
But I do.

9
00:01:15,910 --> 00:01:19,289
So what is it like walking
to go get coffee when you can run

10
00:01:19,372 --> 00:01:20,790
4,000 miles an hour?

11
00:01:20,873 --> 00:01:24,002
It's nice slowing down every once
in a while, even for the Flash.

12
00:01:24,085 --> 00:01:25,211
Is Frost joining us?

13
00:01:25,461 --> 00:01:28,631
No. Last night I sent her on
a two week <i>Eat Pray Love</i> tour

14
00:01:28,715 --> 00:01:30,883
because she's still
pining over Mark Blaine.

15
00:01:31,301 --> 00:01:32,820
I thought
she was mad at him all summer.

16
00:01:32,844 --> 00:01:33,844
And fall.

17
00:01:33,845 --> 00:01:36,389
But she still misses him,
even though I told her

18
00:01:36,472 --> 00:01:38,558
he's a jerk who is
never going to change.

19
00:01:38,850 --> 00:01:40,143
Let me guess, she didn't care?

20
00:01:40,476 --> 00:01:41,477
Yep, she said,

21
00:01:41,686 --> 00:01:43,438
"The heart wants what the heart wants."

22
00:01:43,521 --> 00:01:45,398
She's always been such a romantic.

23
00:01:51,279 --> 00:01:54,407
I have learned one thing
watching Frost go through all this.

24
00:01:54,907 --> 00:01:56,784
For the first time since Ronnie passed,

25
00:01:58,703 --> 00:02:00,705
I think I'm really ready
to get back out there.

26
00:02:01,789 --> 00:02:04,500
I'm... gonna start dating again.

27
00:02:05,001 --> 00:02:07,170
That's awesome.
I'm really happy for you.

28
00:02:07,253 --> 00:02:10,131
Thank you. Now if I can just get
some oat milk for my coffee.

29
00:02:13,301 --> 00:02:15,613
Two bullet trains on the Calvert Railway
are going to collide.

30
00:02:15,637 --> 00:02:17,680
Barry, that's 50 miles
south of Keystone City.

31
00:02:17,764 --> 00:02:18,764
Yeah.

32
00:02:38,242 --> 00:02:40,578
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,
authorities are now confirming</i>

33
00:02:40,662 --> 00:02:45,291
<i>that despite a massive explosion
caused by today's railway accident,</i>

34
00:02:45,375 --> 00:02:49,087
<i>no lives were lost
during this horrific event.</i>

35
00:02:49,420 --> 00:02:52,965
<i>It appears our city
has the Flash to thank once more.</i>

36
00:02:56,469 --> 00:02:58,096
That was amazing!

37
00:02:58,805 --> 00:03:01,057
You got everyone to safety
in what, 20 seconds?

38
00:03:01,265 --> 00:03:03,768
Twelve actually. Try your coffee.

39
00:03:09,732 --> 00:03:12,110
Wow. You have seriously leveled up.

40
00:03:12,735 --> 00:03:14,655
If only you could teach Frost
how to do the same.

41
00:03:14,696 --> 00:03:17,657
I mean, bypassing anyone
who calls themselves "Chillblaine,"

42
00:03:17,740 --> 00:03:19,420
I think would save her
a lot of heartbreak.

43
00:03:19,492 --> 00:03:23,121
I mean, Frost dating anybody,
is a first for her, right?

44
00:03:23,413 --> 00:03:25,039
And everybody you dated before Ronnie,

45
00:03:25,123 --> 00:03:26,749
I'm guessing that was you leveling up.

46
00:03:27,208 --> 00:03:28,334
You know, it's a process.

47
00:03:29,043 --> 00:03:31,546
Maybe just give Frost space
to do the same.

48
00:03:34,298 --> 00:03:37,093
Captain Kramer,
while supportive of your transparency...

49
00:03:37,427 --> 00:03:39,637
...you have been criticized
for your decision

50
00:03:39,721 --> 00:03:41,431
to disband the city's meta task force.

51
00:03:41,514 --> 00:03:44,934
Some people thinking that it will
increase meta-crime across the city.

52
00:03:45,268 --> 00:03:46,436
Do you care to comment?

53
00:03:46,894 --> 00:03:53,234
Once I came to terms with being a meta,
it helped me realize how important it is

54
00:03:53,317 --> 00:03:58,114
for everyone in Central City to receive
equal protections under the same laws.

55
00:03:58,281 --> 00:04:02,326
So you felt as though the meta
task force was unfairly targeting

56
00:04:02,577 --> 00:04:04,328
marginalized sections of the populace.

57
00:04:04,412 --> 00:04:07,039
Yes, which is why its time has passed.

58
00:04:07,373 --> 00:04:09,459
Great. Thank you, Captain Kramer.

59
00:04:09,667 --> 00:04:11,961
This is Iris West-Allen
for <i>Citizentopia.</i>

60
00:04:12,044 --> 00:04:13,254
Thank you for listening.

61
00:04:14,672 --> 00:04:15,757
That was great.

62
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:17,091
It was great. Come in.

63
00:04:17,550 --> 00:04:19,469
Allegra, you remember Captain Kramer?

64
00:04:19,552 --> 00:04:20,552
- Hi.
- Hi.

65
00:04:21,220 --> 00:04:23,765
Well, I have an appointment
with Chief Singh,

66
00:04:23,848 --> 00:04:25,141
so, thanks.

67
00:04:26,809 --> 00:04:27,809
You wanted to see me?

68
00:04:28,603 --> 00:04:32,190
Yes. So the last six months
have been pretty intense.

69
00:04:32,482 --> 00:04:37,445
I'll say. We have three new reporters,
an IT intern and an office manager now.

70
00:04:37,570 --> 00:04:39,989
Plus, online circulation's
over two million,

71
00:04:40,072 --> 00:04:42,241
and your new podcast's
frickin' brilliant.

72
00:04:42,325 --> 00:04:45,286
- Thank you.
- Oh, we need faster internet.

73
00:04:45,369 --> 00:04:46,704
Should we call the new landlord?

74
00:04:46,996 --> 00:04:48,265
Sue Dearbon bought the building.

75
00:04:48,289 --> 00:04:50,166
I think we can fix our own internet.

76
00:04:50,249 --> 00:04:51,249
Roger that.

77
00:04:51,542 --> 00:04:53,711
But seriously, I just
don't see how you do it all

78
00:04:53,795 --> 00:04:55,439
and still find time
for an op-ed each week.

79
00:04:55,463 --> 00:04:56,672
Well, I can't.

80
00:04:57,173 --> 00:04:59,258
So the bullpen needs
a supervising editor.

81
00:04:59,342 --> 00:05:00,944
Someone who decides
which stories we cover

82
00:05:00,968 --> 00:05:03,387
and then assigns and pre-edits copy.

83
00:05:03,971 --> 00:05:07,475
Which is why I am promoting you.

84
00:05:07,683 --> 00:05:09,268
Wha... Iris...

85
00:05:09,811 --> 00:05:12,688
Well, I've barely been staff for a year.

86
00:05:12,772 --> 00:05:14,148
I'm not ready for that.

87
00:05:14,816 --> 00:05:17,944
- Well, I think you are.
- You do realize you have people on staff

88
00:05:18,027 --> 00:05:20,154
who are more qualified
to handle that sort of thing?

89
00:05:20,238 --> 00:05:23,491
I mean, Vanya, she's got ten years
of experience under her belt.

90
00:05:23,574 --> 00:05:24,992
Or that annoying Taylor,

91
00:05:25,076 --> 00:05:28,120
just graduated summa cum laude
from Barnard College.

92
00:05:28,204 --> 00:05:30,623
Even the old guy was a war correspondent
in Beirut.

93
00:05:31,582 --> 00:05:34,710
Aariz is my age. Girl!

94
00:05:39,006 --> 00:05:42,593
Look, now that we're
CC Citizen Media, I am busier

95
00:05:42,677 --> 00:05:44,345
with more and more
administrative duties.

96
00:05:44,804 --> 00:05:47,014
- Iris, are you sure?
- You got this.

97
00:05:47,348 --> 00:05:48,432
I believe in you.

98
00:05:53,479 --> 00:05:55,022
What is this?

99
00:05:55,314 --> 00:05:59,193
A candlelit pizza dinner,
from our favorite place in Milan.

100
00:05:59,277 --> 00:06:02,613
Oh, thank God, I was too tired to cook.

101
00:06:02,697 --> 00:06:04,073
I can't imagine why.

102
00:06:04,156 --> 00:06:06,617
Team Citizen's
been in overdrive these days.

103
00:06:07,118 --> 00:06:08,911
Plus, Deon's still helping to stabilize

104
00:06:08,995 --> 00:06:11,330
your temporal sickness
with regular treatments.

105
00:06:11,706 --> 00:06:12,790
It's a lot to handle.

106
00:06:13,541 --> 00:06:14,625
I told you I'm fine.

107
00:06:14,959 --> 00:06:17,712
Plus, you're not exactly
an underachiever yourself, Flash.

108
00:06:17,795 --> 00:06:19,422
Nice work at Calvert Railway.

109
00:06:19,505 --> 00:06:20,421
Thanks.

110
00:06:20,423 --> 00:06:21,823
I guess we both earned a night off.

111
00:06:21,883 --> 00:06:23,050
And without kids, too.

112
00:06:23,426 --> 00:06:25,404
I mean, don't get me wrong.
It's great having Bart and Nora

113
00:06:25,428 --> 00:06:27,096
stop in all the time from 2049...

114
00:06:27,179 --> 00:06:32,184
But if we're ever going to have a baby,
we need some alone time, Mr. Allen.

115
00:06:36,522 --> 00:06:37,690
- Great.
- Yeah.

116
00:06:39,859 --> 00:06:41,485
- Ray?
- In the flesh.

117
00:06:43,154 --> 00:06:45,698
What, uh... What brings you
to Central City?

118
00:06:45,781 --> 00:06:47,742
Oh, well, you guys said
I could always crash here

119
00:06:47,825 --> 00:06:50,912
if ever I was in town,
and I'm here attending CCTC.

120
00:06:51,162 --> 00:06:54,248
But my hotel is overbooked,
and it's impossible to get

121
00:06:54,332 --> 00:06:55,976
a conference hotel room
at the last minute.

122
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,086
So I figured I'd take you up
on your very kind offer.

123
00:06:59,170 --> 00:07:01,756
- Oh, that makes sense.
- Doesn't it?

124
00:07:03,174 --> 00:07:06,218
Are you guys having pizza?
Is it gluten-free?

125
00:07:06,427 --> 00:07:09,055
- No, it's from Italy.
- Oh.

126
00:07:09,305 --> 00:07:12,308
So, where is Nora?
Did she come with you?

127
00:07:12,391 --> 00:07:14,769
No, she's saving the world
one kid at a time

128
00:07:14,852 --> 00:07:16,270
and loving it.

129
00:07:18,147 --> 00:07:20,483
Am... Am I interrupting?

130
00:07:20,983 --> 00:07:22,360
- Never.
- No.

131
00:07:22,485 --> 00:07:23,611
Really? Great!

132
00:07:24,111 --> 00:07:25,321
So is this a sofa bed

133
00:07:25,404 --> 00:07:27,448
or like a sheets-and-blankets-on-top
sort of thing?

134
00:07:28,532 --> 00:07:30,993
There is a guest bedroom
at the top of the stairs.

135
00:07:31,369 --> 00:07:33,162
Aw! You guys are the best.

136
00:07:34,330 --> 00:07:36,374
- I'll get the rest of my bags later.
- Okay.

137
00:07:39,335 --> 00:07:41,295
- I thought he could shrink things.
- Yeah.

138
00:07:44,006 --> 00:07:45,383
<i>Trucks at loading dock.</i>

139
00:07:45,675 --> 00:07:47,927
Copy that. Transport team's here.

140
00:07:49,845 --> 00:07:50,845
What the hell?

141
00:08:02,191 --> 00:08:04,402
<i>In three seconds,
the two on the outside</i>

142
00:08:04,485 --> 00:08:06,195
<i>will draw their weapons and advance,</i>

143
00:08:06,278 --> 00:08:07,989
<i>while the other two
hold their positions.</i>

144
00:08:08,489 --> 00:08:09,573
<i>Jack, you're up.</i>

145
00:08:14,203 --> 00:08:16,038
I could have melted your faces instead.

146
00:08:16,706 --> 00:08:18,165
Guess you drew a lucky hand.

147
00:08:19,333 --> 00:08:21,311
<i>Ooh, their minds
are full of fear, Ten.</i>

148
00:08:21,335 --> 00:08:23,004
<i>Show them who has the winning hand.</i>

149
00:08:28,175 --> 00:08:30,011
- Jackpot.
- Oh, crap.

150
00:08:31,012 --> 00:08:33,639
<i>My King, you know the drill.</i>

151
00:08:44,233 --> 00:08:45,359
I guess he folded.

152
00:08:45,443 --> 00:08:47,778
- Well, that's no fun.
- Either way,

153
00:08:48,154 --> 00:08:54,243
that was damn fine work, My Queen.

154
00:08:55,286 --> 00:08:58,664
Well, it's easy when you can see
each card before it's dealt.

155
00:09:00,124 --> 00:09:01,292
My Queen.

156
00:09:14,221 --> 00:09:18,642
- Now what?
- We raise the stakes.

157
00:09:28,110 --> 00:09:29,111
There you go, Iris.

158
00:09:30,738 --> 00:09:35,242
Uh, Ray, how often do you talk to Sara
and all the other Legends?

159
00:09:35,659 --> 00:09:37,620
Well, not very often.

160
00:09:37,953 --> 00:09:40,748
Nate and I do have
a standing drinks night once a month,

161
00:09:41,165 --> 00:09:44,335
but he's rarely
in the same century or year.

162
00:09:45,002 --> 00:09:46,855
Yeah, that may be
why I haven't heard from him lately.

163
00:09:46,879 --> 00:09:47,880
I'm sorry.

164
00:09:48,214 --> 00:09:49,214
It's okay.

165
00:09:49,715 --> 00:09:50,715
Kind of.

166
00:09:51,217 --> 00:09:53,677
Yeah, it was really hard
leaving the Legends,

167
00:09:54,386 --> 00:09:58,599
but since then, Nora and I
have been more connected than ever.

168
00:09:58,808 --> 00:10:01,060
And, you know,
I've been able to get back

169
00:10:01,143 --> 00:10:03,771
to my other true love, pure research.

170
00:10:03,854 --> 00:10:05,981
Plus, my life's more balanced now.

171
00:10:06,065 --> 00:10:08,609
It's not just "I'm the Atom,
and science takes a backseat,"

172
00:10:08,692 --> 00:10:12,029
you know so, yeah, to, uh...
To second acts.

173
00:10:14,115 --> 00:10:15,115
I'll get it.

174
00:10:17,326 --> 00:10:20,412
Is this year's Legacy Honoree
in the house?

175
00:10:20,496 --> 00:10:21,736
Hey, Chester. Yeah, come on in.

176
00:10:23,249 --> 00:10:24,959
Chester, Ray. Ray, Chester.

177
00:10:25,042 --> 00:10:27,711
Ah, so you're the new team tech genius.

178
00:10:28,045 --> 00:10:29,130
Nice to meet you, Chester.

179
00:10:29,505 --> 00:10:30,421
Likewise.

180
00:10:30,422 --> 00:10:33,402
I've been a big fan of yours ever since
reading your papers on quantum qubits.

181
00:10:33,425 --> 00:10:35,553
So you're pretty stoked
about the con this year, huh?

182
00:10:35,636 --> 00:10:37,054
Oh, are you kidding me?

183
00:10:37,388 --> 00:10:39,825
Ever since I found out you were
going to be this year's Legacy Honoree,

184
00:10:39,849 --> 00:10:44,145
I kind of took the liberty of signing up
to be a CCTC volunteer.

185
00:10:45,896 --> 00:10:49,650
I'm going to be your liaison
for the entire event, if that's cool.

186
00:10:49,733 --> 00:10:51,569
Like, if you're all right.

187
00:10:51,986 --> 00:10:52,902
Sounds great.

188
00:10:52,903 --> 00:10:56,115
Cool, because I already have your whole
itinerary planned to sweet perfection.

189
00:10:58,242 --> 00:11:00,619
So, um, I'm late for work.

190
00:11:00,703 --> 00:11:03,789
So, Ray, Chester, I'll pop by
the convention center later.

191
00:11:03,873 --> 00:11:05,473
- Don't you dare...
- See ya, I gotta go.

192
00:11:07,626 --> 00:11:09,461
Aw, he forgot his breakfast.

193
00:11:10,671 --> 00:11:14,341
That's a bracelet. You know what?
I have to go, too... deadlines.

194
00:11:14,425 --> 00:11:17,052
You got the list of questions
for the interview later, right?

195
00:11:17,136 --> 00:11:18,804
Sure do. See you at 4:00.

196
00:11:22,975 --> 00:11:25,895
Heard some paroled ex-cons
went shopping without their wallets.

197
00:11:25,978 --> 00:11:27,938
OG meta-criminals, actually.

198
00:11:28,522 --> 00:11:33,402
Jack, Ten, King and the Queen, they
call themselves the Royal Flush Gang.

199
00:11:34,111 --> 00:11:36,197
They were Central City's
very first meta-threat.

200
00:11:36,447 --> 00:11:37,465
You worked that case, too?

201
00:11:37,489 --> 00:11:41,160
Actually, no. The first time
they pulled a job, I was...

202
00:11:45,956 --> 00:11:47,666
...kind of under the weather.

203
00:11:48,500 --> 00:11:53,255
It's weird. Their MO is stealing cash
from casinos, not microchips.

204
00:11:54,506 --> 00:11:58,010
Well, at least no one was killed...
this time.

205
00:11:59,428 --> 00:12:00,638
Everything okay, Captain?

206
00:12:03,724 --> 00:12:07,186
This is the kind of case the meta
task force would have been assigned to.

207
00:12:08,354 --> 00:12:12,149
Uh, so your mimic powers,

208
00:12:12,858 --> 00:12:14,860
how exactly do they work?

209
00:12:15,152 --> 00:12:17,279
They only activate in times of stress,

210
00:12:17,613 --> 00:12:20,658
when my adrenaline spikes,
and the effects are temporary.

211
00:12:21,283 --> 00:12:22,326
That's good.

212
00:12:23,369 --> 00:12:24,369
Yeah.

213
00:12:25,955 --> 00:12:29,166
Allen, does me being a meta
make working for me more difficult?

214
00:12:30,167 --> 00:12:33,754
No, ma'am. It's already
tough enough as it is.

215
00:12:36,966 --> 00:12:39,093
I'll let you know
as soon as I find something.

216
00:12:39,969 --> 00:12:40,969
Okay.

217
00:12:47,268 --> 00:12:49,687
So I've gone over everyone's ideas
and they're great.

218
00:12:49,937 --> 00:12:52,940
But what I'd like to do is start with
last night's break-in at Mercury Labs.

219
00:12:55,818 --> 00:12:58,279
It's not news, not in this city.

220
00:12:58,487 --> 00:13:01,365
It's a high-tech theft
at a huge R&D corporation...

221
00:13:01,448 --> 00:13:03,534
Which happens all the time in this town.

222
00:13:03,784 --> 00:13:05,327
- Was anyone killed?
- No.

223
00:13:05,411 --> 00:13:06,846
- Was the Flash involved?
- No. He isn't.

224
00:13:06,870 --> 00:13:10,749
- Tragedy sells papers, folks. Sorry.
- But... That's not the point.

225
00:13:10,833 --> 00:13:13,395
We should look into the rumors of
embezzlement inside the mayor's office.

226
00:13:13,419 --> 00:13:15,421
Scooping a major scandal
before our competition...

227
00:13:15,504 --> 00:13:16,839
Will make Iris happy.

228
00:13:16,922 --> 00:13:18,525
Get in touch with someone
at the mayor's office.

229
00:13:18,549 --> 00:13:21,176
I got 1,000 words to finish on
the Shark's new GM for Iris, too...

230
00:13:21,260 --> 00:13:23,178
Wait. What 1,000 words?

231
00:13:23,262 --> 00:13:24,823
Well, I know the mayor's
executive assistant.

232
00:13:24,847 --> 00:13:27,266
I need someone on this Mercury break-in.

233
00:13:28,475 --> 00:13:31,395
Vanya, I really need you
to run with this tech heist.

234
00:13:32,604 --> 00:13:35,190
I'm going to follow up
on the Calvert collision this morning.

235
00:13:35,274 --> 00:13:36,874
My source in the county planner's office

236
00:13:36,942 --> 00:13:39,903
says it's going to cost several million
to repair the damage.

237
00:13:40,070 --> 00:13:44,283
Talk about a budget crisis.
Plus, that is what Iris would want.

238
00:13:46,035 --> 00:13:50,414
Well, hold on. Wait, guys... seriously?

239
00:13:54,043 --> 00:13:56,128
We found this
at the train collision site.

240
00:13:56,211 --> 00:13:59,465
I thought Kramer had you working
on the Mercury heist instead.

241
00:13:59,631 --> 00:14:00,631
Yeah, I am.

242
